n%20warships%20at%20the%20Black%20Sea%20Fleet%20base%20in%20Sevastopol%20in%20July%202010.%3Cp%3EAP%20Photo%2FSergey%20Ponomarev%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ESigned%20in%201936%2C%20the%20Montreux%20Convention%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.usni.org%2Fmagazines%2Fproceedings%2F2022%2Fmarch%2Fturkey-montreux-convention-and-russian-navy-transits-turkish%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egoverns%20the%20transit%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20merchant%20vessels%20and%20warships%20through%20the%20Dardanelles%20and%20the%20Bosporus%20Strait%20and%20the%20presence%20of%20warships%20in%20the%20Black%20Sea.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20convention%20distinguishes%20between%20Black%20Sea%20powers%20%E2%80%94%20those%20with%20a%20Black%20Sea%20coastline%20%E2%80%94%20and%20non-Black%20Sea%20powers.%20In%20peacetime%2C%20warships%20belonging%20to%20non-Black%20Sea%20powers%20cannot%20stay%20in%20the%20sea%20for%20more%20than%2021%20days.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20convention%20also%20has%20limits%20for%20the%20combined%20tonnage%20of%20vessels%20from%20non-Black%20Sea%20powers%20that%20can%20be%20in%20the%20sea%20at%20one%20time%2C%20capping%20it%20at%20a%20maximum%20of%2045%2C000%20tons%20with%20no%20more%20than%2030%2C000%20tons%20belonging%20to%20one%20country.%20A%20US%20Navy%20Arleigh%20Burke-class%20destroyer%2C%20several%20of%20which%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fus-navy-warships-in-black-sea-amid-nato-russia-tensions-2021-11%5C%22%3Ehave%20sailed%20into%20the%20sea%20in%20recent%20years%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20is%20about%209%2C000%20tons.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20the%20convention%20doesn't%20specifically%20rule%20out%20aircraft%20carriers%2C%20a%2015%2C000-ton%20limit%20for%20vessels%20of%20non-Black%20Sea%20powers%20transiting%20the%20straits%20effectively%20prohibits%20them.%20Submarines%20from%20non-Black%20Sea%20powers%20are%20also%20not%20allowed.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%224000%5C%22%20alt%